---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import DarkOpener from '../components/DarkOpener.astro';
import DarkResolve from '../components/DarkResolve.astro';
import ThreeColumn from '../components/ThreeColumn.astro';
import EvidenceBand from '../components/EvidenceBand.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="Argo Rannamets: 25 years operating across 100+ companies in 8 countries, in six roles, founder to corporate executive. Operator, not observer. Installer, not trainer."
>
  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 1 — Hero (DarkOpener, navy)
     First-person voice (About-specific). Eyebrow text present.
     Primary line (first-child → opener-lead 26-36px w600), body
     (second p → opener-body 20-28px w400), then the credential spine
     (third p, overridden smaller) — the spine below the body is an
     About-specific pattern. All three spine numerals coppered as one
     rhythmic unit, including spelled-out "six".
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <DarkOpener eyebrow="About Argo Rannamets">
    <p>I help leadership teams do the right things, not just do things right.</p>
    <p>
      For CEOs and leadership teams who have the ambition but not yet the
      execution to match it. Twenty-five years inside these decisions, not
      beside them, across organizations from ten people to 2,500.
    </p>
    <p class="hero-spine">
      <span class="accent">100+</span> companies · <span class="accent">8</span> countries · <span class="accent">six</span> roles · founder to corporate executive
    </p>
  </DarkOpener>

  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 2 — The dual foundation (light)
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <Section
    eyebrow="The combination"
    heading="An operator who understands the systems and the people"
  >
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Most CFOs who turn advisor sell financial rigor. Most coaches who sell
        culture sell soft skills. I spent fifteen years deliberately building
        the second pillar on top of the first: NLP, coaching and mentoring
        training, Radical Collaboration. All of it layered onto a CFO's
        analytical brain.
      </p>
      <p>
        That combination is the whole point. It is why I treat confidence as a
        measurable outcome, not an engagement score. Confidence is what you get
        when mastery meets clarity: when roles are clear, the tools work,
        feedback flows, and people have room to act. Get the system right and
        the confidence follows.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is also why my 45-part culture framework holds up. It is not a
        feel-good model from a psychologist, and it is not a spreadsheet from
        an accountant. It is a structured system built by someone who
        understands both the mechanics and the humans inside them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 3 — The six roles (light)
     H2 left plain (numbers-in-headings stay unaccented, consistent
     with the offering pages).
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <Section
    eyebrow="The six seats"
    heading="100+ companies, seen from six seats"
  >
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Breadth matters because real situations are rarely textbook. The value
        is in having seen enough versions of a problem to recognize it when it
        shows up in a new shape. Someone who ran one company for twenty years
        has depth on one pattern. I've worked across more than a hundred
        companies, in six different roles:
      </p>
    </div>

    <ul class="role-list">
      <li class="role-list__item"><strong>Employee.</strong> Sixteen years scaling Ragn-Sells.</li>
      <li class="role-list__item"><strong>Management Board member.</strong> Around fifteen companies, including Ragn-Sells AS, Ekspress Grupp, and Enefit Green.</li>
      <li class="role-list__item"><strong>Supervisory Board member.</strong> Around twenty companies, including subsidiaries of Ekspress Grupp, Enefit Green, and Ragn-Sells, companies in the utilities sector, and others.</li>
      <li class="role-list__item"><strong>Consultant.</strong> Sixty to seventy customers across several countries in controlling, management accounting, business intelligence, and financial management.</li>
      <li class="role-list__item"><strong>Coach and mentor.</strong> 70+ leaders coached one to one over fifteen years, including Fontes' top tier.</li>
      <li class="role-list__item"><strong>Advisor.</strong> More than forty programs installed through Magere OÜ, my current practice.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Eight countries in all: Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Finland, Poland,
        Sweden, Norway, Denmark. Norway and Denmark are in that count through
        Ragn-Sells Group leadership and the years I led the Ragn-Sells Group
        quality function.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 4 — The evidence (light)
     Copper .accent on €1B, 132, 90%.
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <Section
    eyebrow="The evidence"
    heading="The decisions, not just the advice"
  >
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        <strong>CFO of three Baltic listed companies.</strong> Enefit Green,
        Ekspress Grupp, and Saku Õlletehas, with a Management Board seat at the
        first two. At Enefit Green I carried a <span class="accent">€1B</span>
        loan portfolio, one of the largest in the Baltics. At Ekspress Grupp I
        ran one accelerator across ten of its subsidiaries at the same time.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>I lead with evidence, not instinct.</strong> The seat matters
        less than what you do in it. I once analyzed
        <span class="accent">132</span> management board decisions over six
        months and proved that <span class="accent">90%</span> had only been
        consulted, never actually decided. Most leaders accept the structure
        they inherit. I test it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>I've taken the founder's risk myself.</strong> I co-founded
        KWOTA, a climate tech startup that built the first KPMG-audited global
        standard for verifying carbon savings from recycled material. It didn't
        survive, but I'd do it again if the conditions were as promising as they
        were then.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>TalTech had me teach the roadmap I already use.</strong> I
        taught strategic management at its eMBA, built around the six-stage
        roadmap I run in practice today.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Fontes send me their hardest assignments.</strong> And the
        pairings that have already broken down, the ones that need someone to
        take over and finish.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 5 — How I work (ThreeColumn, stone)
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <Section
    variant="stone"
    eyebrow="How I work"
    heading="Three things that don't change"
  >
    <ThreeColumn>
      <div class="three-col__item">
        <h3>Pragmatic &amp; focused</h3>
        <p>
          I cut through complexity to the critical drivers. A 20/80 mindset
          that gets maximum leverage from your team's time.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="three-col__item">
        <h3>Full confidence during change</h3>
        <p>
          Doubts get eliminated during implementation. Executives come back to
          say thank you.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="three-col__item">
        <h3>Owner's mindset &amp; human-centric</h3>
        <p>
          I think like an owner, not a consultant. Highly structured
          systems-thinking with a deep focus on people.
        </p>
      </div>
    </ThreeColumn>
  </Section>

  {/* Section 6 — EvidenceBand placeholder (invisible at launch) */}
  <EvidenceBand placeholder={true} />

  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 7 — Closer (DarkResolve, navy band)
     Two-line signature at full display weight, consistent with the
     RTN and EP closers. Line 1 white, line 2 copper, centered,
     eyebrow rule with no eyebrow text.
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <DarkResolve
    line1="Operator, not observer."
    line2="Installer, not trainer."
  />

  {/* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Section 8 — CTA (light)
     No eyebrow — H2 is the framing. Two routes (About-specific):
     primary to the flagship offering, secondary to contact.
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <Section heading="Where to start">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        If you want to see how I actually work, the offerings lay it out, from
        a single advisory seat to the full fourteen-week build.
      </p>
      <p>
        And if you're carrying a decision you can't take to anyone else, that's
        usually where the first conversation starts.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="cta-actions">
      <Button href="/right-things-nailed/" arrow={true}>See the offerings</Button>
      <Button href="/contact/" variant="secondary" arrow={true}>Start a conversation</Button>
    </div>
  </Section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Hero credential spine (Section 1) — About-specific.
     Sits below the body inside the DarkOpener navy band, smaller
     than the body lines. Higher specificity than DarkOpener's
     .do__body :global(p) so the size override wins. Copper numerals
     already colored by DarkOpener's .do__body :global(.accent) rule.
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  :global(.do__body .hero-spine) {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: clamp(1rem, 0.4vw + 0.85rem, 1.125rem); /* 16-18px */
    font-weight: var(--weight-medium);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-normal);
    color: var(--color-on-dark-muted);
    margin-top: var(--space-8); /* set apart from the body line */
    text-wrap: balance;
  }

  /* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     Six-roles list (Section 3) — copper-bullet markers, bold role
     labels. Same bullet treatment as the offering-page Format lists.
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .role-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-8) 0;
  }

  .role-list__item {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
    color: var(--color-slate-600);
  }

  .role-list__item:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .role-list__item :global(strong) {
    font-weight: var(--weight-semibold);
    color: var(--color-slate-900);
  }

  .role-list__item::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.65em;
    width: 6px;
    height: 6px;
    background: var(--color-copper);
  }

  /* ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     CTA action row (Section 8) — two buttons, About routes two ways.
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .cta-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
  }
</style>
